          }}></path></svg></a>{`The Incident Link Process in 3.2`}</h2>
    <p>{`Before the introduction of synchronous incident creation in the REST API, the integration app would use the following process to link incidents between systems:`}</p>
    <ol>
      <li parentName="ol">{`A ServiceNow incident triggers a PagerDuty incident.`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`When the event is received through the PagerDuty Events API, The ServiceNow incident's PagerDuty incident ID field is set to `}<inlineCode parentName="li">{`---waiting---`}</inlineCode>{`, and the incident key is set based on the response from the API. At this point in time, the incident ID, which is needed for the full bidirectional integration, is not available.`}{`*`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`The event from ServiceNow, through the Events API, triggers a resulting incident.`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`The webhook extension for the service on which the incident is triggered sends a webhook payload of type `}<inlineCode parentName="li">{`incident.trigger`}</inlineCode>{` back to ServiceNow. The payload contains both the incident key and the incident ID.`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`ServiceNow receives and processes the webhook payload into a webhook import row`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`The `}<strong parentName="li">{`PagerDuty Webhook Import`}</strong>{` table transform map finds the ServiceNow record with a query on the incident key field, `}<inlineCode parentName="li">{`x_pd_integration_incident_key`}</inlineCode>{`.`}</li>
      <li parentName="ol">{`The import transform map updates the incident ID field, and the incident is linked.`}</li>
    </ol>
    <p>{`For this reason, ServiceNow-integrated services (with ServiceNow integration app version 3.2.x could not be configured to create alerts and incidents, because this deprecates the incident key, making it null in webhooks, and thus rendering the webhook import unable to find existing records. Refer to `}<a parentName="p" {...{
        "href": "/docs/alerts#section-alerts-and-bidirectional-integrations"
      }}>{`Alerts and bidirectional integrations`}</a>{` for further details.`}</p>
    <p>{`This also formed the basis for many difficult issues that arose in customized ServiceNow integration apps. If troubleshooting an integration app that is based on 3.2.x and has been customized, it is recommended that you log the value of the incident key field and enable it in list/form views, to identify if anything happens to it that would interfere with the integration process.`}</p>
    <p>{`*`}{` `}<em parentName="p">{`For the curious:`}</em>{` the advantage behind this design is to be able to process and deduplicate potentially far higher quantities of data more efficiently, before creating from the events (or de-duplicating events into) corresponding incidents. Incidents represent actionable items for humans to work on resolving, versus events/alerts, which represent data from monitoring tools, and can be noisy / overabundant.`}</p>

